    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with significant firepower at the top of the order, headlined by **Junior Caminero** (76.66) and **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (75.47). **Junior Caminero** is our strongest play; he benefits from a favorable matchup against Keller and a rare combination of positive park factors and wind blowing out, significantly elevating his ceiling in the two-hole. **Pete Crow-Armstrong** provides elite upside despite an eight-hole assignment, as the dynamic platoon advantage against Myers outweighs his lower spot in the order. Similarly, **Trea Turner** (69.15) remains a cornerstone, with his leadoff position and favorable matchup against Holmes providing the high-floor production we need to remain competitive in the SB category.\n\nOur most difficult bench decision involved **Josh Smith** (40.62), who narrowly missed the cut behind the efficiency of **Caleb Durbin** (52.14). While **Josh Smith** projects as a viable utility option, **Caleb Durbin** holds the edge today due to his high-volume stolen base threat against a slower delivery from Valdez, which aligns perfectly with our organizational strategy of overweighting speed in 5x5 Roto formats. Meanwhile, we continue to monitor the status of **Christian Yelich** and **Zac Veen**, both of whom remain unavailable, leaving our depth restricted to the current active roster.\n\nRisk management remains paramount, particularly regarding the volatility of our catching tandem. **Dillon Dingler** (48.35) faces the elite arm of Crochet, necessitating a cautious outlook despite his platoon advantage. Furthermore, while **Victor Scott II** (47.23) is in the lineup, his low order spot and negative park factors cap his efficiency today; we are prioritizing his defensive and base-stealing utility over raw scoring potential. We will keep a close eye on **Gary Sanchez**, whose sub-50 score reflects the difficulty of facing P\u00e9rez, though his presence in the three-hole offers some insulation against a total collapse in production.",
